<article id="post-1028" class="post-1028 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-costa-rica category-general category-technology tag-gsm tag-mobile tag-phones">
	<header class="entry-header">
		
		<h2 class="entry-title"><a href="http://geoff.wp/2008/08/my-new-1998-era-nokia-tdma-cell-phone/" rel="bookmark">My new 1998-era Nokia TDMA cell phone</a></h2>	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	
	
	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>Note today&#8217;s date: 8 August 2008. That&#8217;s (almost) two months since we first came to Costa Rica. Two months ago, <a href="http://www.sowrey.org/2008/06/its-manana-time/">we tried to start getting things</a> like cars, bank accounts, work visas (a fairly significant need), and cell phones, as these were the things we felt were necessary to be able to do our jobs effectively.<br />
To date, we&#8217;ve all managed to get bank accounts. Only <a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/sowrey/2723556436/">Mark has successfully bought a car</a> (Jason and Jen are still looking, and we&#8217;re <a href="http://twitter.com/sowrey/statuses/879475198">still waiting for our money to arrive from Canada</a>), and the work visas are in the application process (read: not completed).<br />
Yesterday, despite phones ordered via eBay still being stuck in Costa Rica customs, we finally got cell phones.<br />
